\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 proposition:
\f1\b0 \cf2  if P is a projection on a normed vector space V, then}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 HelveticaNeue-Bold;\f1\fnil\fcharset0 HelveticaNeue;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red6\green53\blue51;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 projection theorem: 
\f1\b0 \cf2 Let M be a finite-dimensional subspace of an inner product space V and P the orthogonal projection with ran P = M. for all y in V, and all x in M, ||y-x||^2 = ||y-Py||^2 + ||Py-x||^2. in particular Py is the closest vector in M to y. If \{e_n\} is an orthonormal basis for M, then Py = sum(<y, e_j>e_j)
\f0\b \cf2  }

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 HelveticaNeue-Light;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red6\green53\blue51;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 section 7.5 finite orthonormal sets}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 HelveticaNeue-Light;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red6\green53\blue51;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 a well-defined inner product on PC[-pi, pi] given by <f, g> = 1/2pi * integral(from -pi to pi) f(x)g(x)dx}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
